[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] Notice that `fruits` and `moreFruits` remain unchanged.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] This example shows three ways to create a new array from the existing `fruits` array: first by using spread syntax, then by using the `from()` method, and then by using the `slice()` method.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] All built-in array-copy operations (spread syntax, `Array.from()`, `Array.prototype.slice()`, and `Array.prototype.concat()`) create shallow copies.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] If you instead want a deep copy of an array, you can use `JSON.stringify()` to convert the array to a JSON string, and then `JSON.parse()` to convert the string back into a new array that's completely independent from the original array.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] You can also create deep copies using the `structuredClone()` method, which has the advantage of allowing transferable objects in the source to be *transferred* to the new copy, rather than just cloned.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] Finally, it's important to understand that assigning an existing array to a new variable doesn't create a copy of either the array or its elements.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] Instead the new variable is just a reference, or alias, to the original array; that is, the original array's name and the new variable name are just two names for the exact same object (and so will always evaluate as strictly equivalent).
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-array] The following creates a chessboard as a two-dimensional array of strings.
