[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] The **`Object`** type represents one of JavaScript's data types.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] It is used to store various keyed collections and more complex entities.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Objects can be created using the `Object()` constructor or the object initializer / literal syntax.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Nearly all objects in JavaScript are instances of `Object`; a typical object inherits properties (including methods) from `Object.prototype`, although these properties may be shadowed (a.k.a. overridden).
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] The only objects that don't inherit from `Object.prototype` are those with `null` prototype, or descended from other `null` prototype objects.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Changes to the `Object.prototype` object are seen by **all** objects through prototype chaining, unless the properties and methods subject to those changes are overridden further along the prototype chain.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] This provides a very powerful although potentially dangerous mechanism to override or extend object behavior.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] To make it more secure, `Object.prototype` is the only object in the core JavaScript language that has immutable prototype — the prototype of `Object.prototype` is always `null` and not changeable.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] You should avoid calling any of the `Object.prototype` methods directly from the instance, especially those that are not intended to be polymorphic (i.e., only its initial behavior makes sense and no descending object could override it in a meaningful way).
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] All objects descending from `Object.prototype` may define a custom own property that has the same name, but with entirely different semantics from what you expect.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Furthermore, these properties are not inherited by `null`-prototype objects.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] All modern JavaScript utilities for working with objects are static.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] There isn't any method in an Object itself to delete its own properties (such as `Map.prototype.delete()`).
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] To do so, one must use the `delete` operator.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Almost all objects in JavaScript ultimately inherit from `Object.prototype` (see inheritance and the prototype chain).
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] However, you may create `null`-prototype objects using `Object.create(null)` or the object initializer syntax with `__proto__: null` (note: the `__proto__` key in object literals is different from the deprecated `Object.prototype.__proto__` property).
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] You can also change the prototype of an existing object to `null` by calling `Object.setPrototypeOf(obj, null)`.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] An object with a `null` prototype can behave in unexpected ways, because it doesn't inherit any object methods from `Object.prototype`.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] This is especially true when debugging, since common object-property converting/detecting utility functions may generate errors, or lose information (especially if using silent error-traps that ignore errors).
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Unlike normal objects, in which `toString()` is on the object's prototype, the `toString()` method here is an own property of `nullProtoObj`.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] This is because `nullProtoObj` has no (`null`) prototype.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] You can also revert a null-prototype object back to an ordinary object using `Object.setPrototypeOf(nullProtoObj, Object.prototype)`.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] In practice, objects with `null` prototype are usually used as a cheap substitute for maps.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] In such case, the addition of any method should be done cautiously, as they can be confused with the other key-value pairs stored as data.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Making your object not inherit from `Object.prototype` also prevents prototype pollution attacks.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] If a malicious script adds a property to `Object.prototype`, it will be accessible on every object in your program, except objects that have null prototype.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] JavaScript also has built-in APIs that produce `null`-prototype objects, especially those that use objects as ad hoc key-value collections.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] The term "`null`-prototype object" often also includes any object without `Object.prototype` in its prototype chain.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Such objects can be created with `extends null` when using classes.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Many built-in operations that expect objects first coerce their arguments to objects.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] There are two ways to achieve nearly the same effect in JavaScript.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] Unlike conversion to primitives, the object coercion process itself is not observable in any way, since it doesn't invoke custom code like `toString` or `valueOf` methods.
