[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] When altering the behavior of existing `Object.prototype` methods, consider injecting code by wrapping your extension before or after the existing logic.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] For example, this (untested) code will pre-conditionally execute custom logic before the built-in logic or someone else's extension is executed.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] When modifying prototypes with hooks, pass `this` and the arguments (the call state) to the current behavior by calling `apply()` on the function.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] This pattern can be used for any prototype, such as `Node.prototype`, `Function.prototype`, etc.
[src:yargs-cli/global-objects-object] You can read more about prototypes in Inheritance and the prototype chain.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In computer programming, **standard streams** are preconnected input and output communication channels between a computer program and its environment when it begins execution.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The three input/output (I/O) connections are called **standard input** (**stdin**), **standard output** (**stdout**) and **standard error** (**stderr**).
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Originally I/O happened via a physically connected system console (input via keyboard, output via monitor), but standard streams abstract this.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] When a command is executed via an interactive shell, the streams are typically connected to the text terminal on which the shell is running, but can be changed with redirection or a pipeline.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] More generally, a child process inherits the standard streams of its parent process.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Users generally know standard streams as input and output channels that handle data coming from an input device, or that write data from the application.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The data may be text with any encoding, or binary data.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] When a program is run as a daemon, its standard error stream is redirected into a log file, typically for error analysis purposes.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Streams may be used to chain applications, meaning that the output stream of one program can be redirected to be the input stream to another application.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In many operating systems this is expressed by listing the application names, separated by the vertical bar character, for this reason often called the pipeline character.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] A well-known example is the use of a pagination application, such as more, providing the user control over the display of the output stream on the display.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In most operating systems predating Unix, programs had to explicitly connect to the appropriate input and output devices.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] OS-specific intricacies caused this to be a tedious programming task.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] On many systems it was necessary to obtain control of environment settings, access a local file table, determine the intended data set, and handle hardware correctly in the case of a punch card reader, magnetic tape drive, disk drive, line printer, card punch, or interactive terminal.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] One of Unix's several groundbreaking advances was *abstract devices*, which removed the need for a program to know or care what kind of devices it was communicating with.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Older operating systems forced upon the programmer a record structure and frequently non-orthogonal data semantics and device control.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Unix eliminated this complexity with the concept of a data stream: an ordered sequence of data bytes which can be read until the end of file.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] A program may also write bytes as desired and need not, and cannot easily declare their count or grouping.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In contrast, previous operating systems usually required some—often complex—job control language to establish connections, or the equivalent burden had to be orchestrated by the program.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Since Unix provided standard streams, the Unix C runtime environment was obliged to support it as well.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] As a result, most C runtime environments (and C's descendants), regardless of the operating system, provide equivalent functionality.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Standard input is a stream from which a program reads its input data.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The program requests data transfers by use of the *read* operation.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] For example, the *dir* and *ls* programs (which display file names contained in a directory) may take command-line arguments, but perform their operations without any stream data input.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard input is inherited from the parent process.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually associated with the input device of a terminal (or pseudo terminal) which is ultimately linked to a user's keyboard.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] On POSIX systems, the file descriptor for standard input is 0 (zero); the POSIX `<unistd.h>` definition is `STDIN_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` abstraction is provided via the `stdin` (of type `FILE*`) global variable.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Similarly in C++, the global object `std::cin` (of type `std::istream`). provided in `<iostream>`, provides an abstraction via C++ streams.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Similar abstractions exist in the standard I/O libraries of practically every programming language.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Standard output is a stream to which a program writes its output data.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The program requests data transfer with the *write* operation.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] For example, the *file rename* command (variously called *mv*, *move*, or *ren*) is silent on success.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Unless redirected, standard output is inherited from the parent process.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In the case of an interactive shell, that is usually the text terminal which initiated the program.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Standard error is another output stream typically used by programs to output error messages or diagnostics.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] It is a stream independent of standard output and can be redirected separately.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] This solves the semi-predicate problem, allowing output and errors to be distinguished, and is analogous to a function returning a pair of values – see Semipredicate problem § Multivalued return.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The usual destination is the text terminal which started the program to provide the best chance of being seen even if *standard output* is redirected (so not readily observed).
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] For example, output of a program in a pipeline is redirected to input of the next program or a text file, but user prompts and errors from each program still go directly to the text terminal so they can be reviewed by the user in real time.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] It is acceptable and normal to direct *standard output* and *standard error* to the same destination, such as the text terminal.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Messages appear in the same order as the program writes them, unless buffering is involved.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] For example, in common situations the standard error stream is unbuffered but the standard output stream is line-buffered; in this case, text written to standard error later may appear on the terminal earlier, if the standard output stream buffer is not yet full.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The file descriptor for standard error is defined by POSIX as 2 (two); the *<unistd.h>* header file provides the symbol `STDERR_FILENO`; the corresponding C `<stdio.h>` variable is `stderr` (of type `FILE*`).
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Similarly, C++ provides two global objects associated with this stream: `std::cerr` and `std::clog` (each of type `std::ostream`), in `<iostream>`, with the former being unbuffered and the latter using the same buffering mechanism as all other C++ streams.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Standard error was added to Unix in the 1970s after several wasted phototypesetting runs ended with error messages being typeset instead of displayed on the user's terminal.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Fortran has the equivalent of Unix file descriptors: By convention, many Fortran implementations use unit numbers `UNIT=5` for stdin, `UNIT=6` for stdout and `UNIT=0` for stderr.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In Fortran 2003, the intrinsic `ISO_FORTRAN_ENV` module was standardized to include the named constants `INPUT_UNIT`, `OUTPUT_UNIT`, and `ERROR_UNIT` to portably specify the unit numbers.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] ALGOL 60 was criticized for having no standard file access.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] ALGOL 68's input and output facilities were collectively referred to as the transput.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Koster coordinated the definition of the *transput* standard.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The model included three standard channels: `stand in`, `stand out`, and `stand back`.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In the C programming language, the standard input, output, and error streams are attached to the existing Unix file descriptors 0, 1 and 2 respectively.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In a POSIX environment the *<unistd.h>* definitions STDIN_FILENO, STDOUT_FILENO or STDERR_FILENO should be used instead rather than magic numbers.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] File pointers stdin, stdout, and stderr are also provided.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Ken Thompson (designer and implementer of the original Unix operating system) modified sort in Version 5 Unix to accept "-" as representing standard input, which spread to other utilities and became a part of the operating system as a special file in Version 8.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Diagnostics were part of standard output through Version 6, after which Dennis M.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Ritchie created the concept of standard error.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In C++, writing to standard streams was originally done using the `<iostream>` header and its streams, until the release of `<print>` which simplified input/output using print functions.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] C++ inherits C I/O facilities, but it is considered more idiomatic to use the newer C++ facilities.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In Java, the standard streams are referred to by `System.in` (for stdin), `System.out` (for stdout), and `System.err` (for stderr).
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] It is also possible to read from any input stream using a `Scanner`.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In C# and other .NET languages, the standard streams are referred to by `System.Console.In` (for stdin), `System.Console.Out` (for stdout) and `System.Console.Error` (for stderr).
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Basic read and write capabilities for the stdin and stdout streams are also accessible directly through the class `System.Console` (e.g.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] `System.Console.WriteLine()` can be used instead of `System.Console.Out.WriteLine()`).
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] `System.Console.In`, `System.Console.Out` and `System.Console.Error` are respectively `System.IO.TextReader` (stdin) and `System.IO.TextWriter` (stdout, stderr) objects, which only allow access to the underlying standard streams on a text basis.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Full binary access to the standard streams must be performed through the `System.IO.Stream` objects returned by `System.Console.OpenStandardInput()`, `System.Console.OpenStandardOutput()` and `System.Console.OpenStandardError()` respectively.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] When applying the `System.Diagnostics.Process` class one can use the instance properties `StandardInput`, `StandardOutput`, and `StandardError` of that class to access the standard streams of the process.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The following example, written in Python, shows how to redirect the standard input both to the standard output and to a text file.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] In C++23, an updated printing interface was created for writing to the output stream, using `std::print` functions.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) do not always make use of the standard streams; they do when GUIs are wrappers of underlying scripts and/or console programs, for instance the Synaptic package manager GUI, which wraps apt commands in Debian and/or Ubuntu.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] GUIs created with scripting tools like Zenity and KDialog by KDE project make use of stdin, stdout, and stderr, and are based on simple scripts rather than a complete GUI programmed and compiled in C/C++ using Qt, GTK, or other equivalent proprietary widget framework.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The Services menu, as implemented on NeXTSTEP and Mac OS X, is also analogous to standard streams.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] On these operating systems, graphical applications can provide functionality through a system-wide menu that operates on the current selection in the GUI, no matter in what application.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Some GUI programs, primarily on Unix, still write debug information to standard error.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Others (such as many Unix media players) may read files from standard input.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] Popular Windows programs that open a separate console window in addition to their GUI windows are the emulators pSX and DOSBox.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] GTK-server can use stdin as a communication interface with an interpreted program to realize a GUI.
[src:yargs-cli/standard-streams] The Common Lisp Interface Manager paradigm "presents" GUI elements sent to an extended output stream.
[src:yargs-cli/yargs-yargs] Yargs helps you build interactive command line tools, by parsing arguments and generating an elegant user interface.
[src:yargs-cli/yargs-yargs] Run the example above with `--help` to see the help for the application.
